CONSENT: Consent Statement    Please review the following information about this study.   	 	TASK: If you agree to participate in this study, we will ask you to answer a series of questions about a series of images.  	 	 	BENEFITS:  There will be no direct benefits to you other than compensation. 	 	 	RISKS: We don't anticipate any risks from participating in this study to be greater than normal activity. 	 	 	PRIVACY:  No personally identifying information will be revealed to anyone other than the researchers conducting this study. The records of this study will be kept private. We do not collect any personally-identifying information.   	 	 	SECURITY: All records pertaining to this research are stored on encrypted servers. Only the researchers will have access to the records. 	 	 	CHOICE:  Participating in this study is completely voluntary. If you decline to participate, it will not affect your current or future relationship with the researchers. 	 	 	WITHDRAWAL: If you agree to participate, you are free to withdraw at any time. You can withdraw by closing the browser window. If you withdraw, your responses will not be recorded.  	 	 	QUESTIONS: You may ask any questions about the research at any time. If you have questions about the research after you complete the task, please contact Arvind Satyanarayan. 	 	 	QUESTIONS: If you are not satisfied with response of research team, have more questions, or want to talk with someone about your rights as a research participant, you should contact the MIT Committee on the Use of Humans as Experimental Subjects (COUHES).
ELIGIBILITY: Eligibility    You are eligible for this study if and only if:   	You are over 18 years of age. 	You are sighted and do not have color blindness or other color vision impairment. 	You are comfortable reading and writing in English. 	You have JavaScript enabled in your browser.

0_Q_B0_MAKER_DETAIL: one of the many online news sites that is mostly clickbait content
0_Q_B0_MAKER_EXPLAIN: The graphic design here is more about being eye-catching and fun than actually being informative; the plants don't give a very accurate way of seeing the exact measurements, so it makes more sense that this is an infographic used more for catching attention than being purely informative. It reminds me a lot of the sort of style used in clickbait articles about saving the environment or new diet trends or similar subjects; the sort of stuff that's supposed to appeal to the younger, leftist population, but is not really caring about being truthful. It feels like something that is meant to generate a response instead of genuinely considering how best to educate someone.
0_Q_B0_TOOL_DETAIL: A lot of software used for proper data visualization will focus more on practicality than having fancy aesthetics, and this leans much further into graphic design than data analysis in my opinion. Not only are the plants a detailed texture that does not lend well to a bar graph format, but the x axis seems to be some sort of gradual scale that is not usually used with a bar graph format. Software that is meant for data visualization will usually not go for this sort of format of displaying the data. Both bar graphs and histograms don't use a sliding scale with no markings on the x axis other than the extremes, so that combined with the graphics used makes me think this is someone designing the graph in some kind of graphic design software.  It's hard to say exactly what software, but I do think this would be easier to achieve in something more high-end, especially considering the complexity of the plant patterns changing to presumably tell something.
0_Q_B0_CHART_ACTION: share / repost WITH comment,look up more information about the topic or source,NOTHING — just keep scrolling
0_Q_B0_CHART_EXPLAIN: Depending on the topic and how relevant it is to me, I would likely either look at further sources, keep scrolling, or reblog with my own commentary. This graph looks like it was meant to draw attention rather than be accurate, and if I care about the subject, I would much rather find more sources to either back up the data or disprove it. I don't like to trust only one source, and I like being able to see how exactly data was gathered and used, instead of just trusting that the graph will be accurate and unbiased.  I rarely block/unfollow for things like these, since they can be an avenue into further learning. I also would rarely repost something that is not undoubtedly good science; the only time I would do so is if I have more information to add to clarify the situation/add more sources.
1_Q_B2_MAKER_EXPLAIN: This graph very much looks like one I would expect to see in my high school or college textbooks. There's not really much to infer about the person that created this in terms of their own personal beliefs and values, since it seems to have been made in a way that is meant to appear as unbiased as possible. It is simple data visualization, and appears to be done by someone that knows how to analyze data well. It is perfectly readable, so I think they are adequate in graphic design, but the use of so many blues in dramatically different shades makes me think they aren't exactly a professional.  I don't have many opinions on what this person might be like based on a graph like this, but my own bias would be towards assuming they are older, since most textbooks I own and read are by people that are older. I would also say they somewhat share my values and are at least some kind of trustworthy, since they seem to care about accurate, clear data representation!

With how simple the chart is, it seems like this is the sort of data that I would be comfortable working with and forming my own opinions on the raw data, so it's something that I would feel confident adding my own information about after doing some research!  If it wasn't a topic of interest, though, I would likely do nothing and keep scrolling.
3_Q_B2_MAKER_DETAIL: A news outlet with a more "professional" sort of persona; something like NYT or other similar news sources
3_Q_B2_MAKER_EXPLAIN: This image is quite a complex map, and I imagine it is something you would need some skill in graphic design to be able to do. It's not very readable, though, so I feel like whoever made it may not have the best grasp on how to best present data, even though they may have experience working with it. I'm not very confident on any other assumptions about this person, but I do imagine it is likely someone with a lot of experience in the field of graphic design that works for some sort of news company, so I would not be surprised if they were a millennial or older.

It is simple enough of a design that it likely could be made in data visualization software, but I can't imagine being able to make something like this purely in graphic design software.
3_Q_B2_CHART_ACTION: look up more information about the topic or source,NOTHING — just keep scrolling
3_Q_B2_CHART_EXPLAIN: The way this visualization is presented makes it seem much more like something one is meant to glance at briefly than actually study in detail, since it is not easy to discern any concrete data from it. If it was a topic I was interested in, I would definitely want more information. I don't have any reason to doubt the accuracy of the information used any more than my usual caution with any information, but because it is so difficult to get anything more than broad generalizations from this, I would very much want a different source. If it was not something I was interested in, then I would likely just keep scrolling.
4_Q_B2_MAKER_DETAIL: definitely some sort of political party instead of an official government source
4_Q_B2_MAKER_EXPLAIN: The infographic definitely appears to be something related to politics, and reminds me a lot of reactionary infographics that, for some reason, tend to more often be right-leaning when made in this style. The person definitely seems to have some skill in graphic design, but don't seem to care much about proper data visualization. Especially looking at the numbers of the left and middle bar graphs, it's interesting to me how the leftmost graph has the highest number of $920, but is still shorter than the highest bar of the middle graph, which reaches only $206. It is also missing an obvious area for units (perhaps some are being measured in millions and others in thousands, which could explain the choice of bar heights, but would still be very misleading), so it really makes me think that these graphs don't care about being accurate data representation. Putting data side-by-side and designing it in a way that makes it easy to get an inaccurate representation of the numbers is something often done in graphic design in order to trick the vast majority of the audience that wouldn't pay attention to the details. This makes me think this person has a good degree of skill in graphic design, and is willing to use it to purposely mislead the audience. As such, I don't find them to be very trustworthy.
4_Q_B2_TOOL_DETAIL: Some sort of graphic design software seems most likely to me, or a combination of data visualization and graphic design. This is definitely something that is achieveable without data visualization software, and has details that would most likely be achieveable with graphic design software, such as the images hanging off the beds and the varied perspective angles.
4_Q_B2_CHART_ACTION: look up more information about the topic or source
4_Q_B2_CHART_EXPLAIN: I don't much like talking about politics on social media, so it is unlikely that I would share something like this other than in incredibly specific situations. However, I do live in the United States, so it is likely something that is relevant to me, and I would want more information on the topic. Especially when it comes to things that are politically motivated, I never trust just one source, and definitely not one made in a way that might be misleading. I would want to look up more sources in order to form my own opinion.
PURPOSE: To see the biases people hold towards different ways of conveying data, and how this affects the way they interact with it.
FEEDBACK: I think the design of this study is quite solid! I'm very glad that questions didn't just ask for an opinion and assume it was a solid one; having the ability to rank how sure you were of your answer, as well as free response, is something I think is very effective in being able to collect more accurate data. The design was very intuitive and seems like it will provide a lot of useful data!

0_Q_B0_MAKER_DETAIL: someone who is interested in something like plant ecology and is in school studying it. they are passionate enough about the subject and/or about sharing what they learn to create a visual to explain something. I think they're young and early in their education because they've chosen a fun but difficult-to-read way to represent each bar - the bars blur together because of lack of definition/space between them, and the tops aren't flat, making it tricky to ascertain where they end. this is the kind of choice I associate with someone who's tired of looking at boring graphs but hasn't yet grasped the importance of readability and clarity in conveying information.
0_Q_B0_MAKER_EXPLAIN: Generation: the use of pink instead of white for the background and the use of fun but difficult-to-read designs for the bars indicate to me someone who wants to do things differently but doesn't yet grasp why the standard ways of representing data exist. Female: the choice of pink, I guess. Graphic design: I think a professional would make the boundaries of each bar clearer Data analysis: there isn't much to go off of. Left-wing: I associate interest in plant ecology/conservation with leftist ideals, but these fields are by no means restricted to leftists. Diplomatic: the soft pink and fun bar designs indicate to me someone who wants to invite people to learn more, to meet them where they're at, not someone who wants to confront and potentially offend them. Altruistic: in my experience, people interested in plant ecology and in sharing their knowledge about it want to improve the state of conservation and/or other people's relationships with plants. Shares my values: if they are a conservationist, they share my values regarding conservation. But I have no idea if they share other values with me. Un/trustworthy: the enthusiasm with which they approach the subject is trustworthy to me, but because I've assumed they're inexperienced in some way, I don't necessarily trust their ability to analyze and accurately interpret data.

The numbers and words are organized in a way that looks like a template, which might be found in a basic graphic design tool. I know from experience that using the graph generator in a word processor wouldn't allow for bars that look like that - even if you can use a texture/image instead of solid colors, the edges would be neat. I expect data visualization software would produce something similar to a word processor. I don't know what kind of graph one could produce through coding though, so maybe this was done via coding.
0_Q_B0_CHART_TYPE: I've always called them bar graphs/charts but I think technically that's only if the bars are horizontal. I don't remember what it's called when they're vertical.

2_Q_B4_MAKER_EXPLAIN: I'll be honest, a lot of my attention is consumed by figuring out what's going on with the words. Google translate doesn't detect them as another language, and I don't think you scrambled the letters of each word. Maybe you scrambled the letters of each label and divided them randomly into words? But when I put any label in an anagram solver there's no results... In any case, the "EY 2012" in the title makes me think this is a quarterly or year-end (EY?) report for a business, made by a random person in the office - so probably middle-aged, maybe male. This is very Microsoft Word - the unappetizing color scheme, the lines connecting labels to their wedges, the way it's 3d for some reason. Therefore, I believe this person has very little experience with graphic design. As a random person in a business office, they might have some experience with data analysis, but not a lot. This image tells me nothing about their politics, intentions, values, or trustworthiness, only that they're not experienced enough with Word to even change the colors because I refuse to believe they wanted brown and blue. They might be a little selfish, but that association is primarily from my reasoning that this is a report for a business, and I associate capitalism with selfishness. But the individual person who made the graph might not be selfish at all.

3_Q_B4_MAKER_EXPLAIN: If they're publishing in a research journal, they have to be older. If not Gen X, then late Millennial or Boomer. I have no way of determining their gender. I wouldn't say they're professional in graphic design but rather experienced. they know that simple shapes are good for data markers and that latitude/longitude can be marked with alternating black and white blocks that line up on both sides of the visual (making it easier for the reader to track where the latitude/longitude lines are throughout the visual). For political alignment, altruism, and values, I cannot make judgements. I know that this is telling me something about ocean temperatures in the southern Atlantic (between South America and Africa), but that doesn't tell me anything about their politics, intentions, or values. I suppose they're somewhat more confrontational than diplomatic because this is a straightforward, direct visualization. I think they're very trustworthy because (reputable) journals put articles through multiple rounds of vetting, so theoretically any inaccuracies in data analysis would be caught.

0_Q_B0_MAKER_EXPLAIN: Oops, answered a little bit of this in the previous answer (sorry). Age was difficult - I put Millennial, but I was torn between that and Gen Z. Partially because to me this image shows a slightly conflicting mix of knowledge of graphic design and displaying data. It's not a bad image from a graphic design standpoint, mostly because the complicated data bars would have taken time and effort. The background color is a little jarring, but not bad. The biggest problem is the complicated design of the data bars distracts somewhat from the actual data being displayed and makes it difficult to determine exactly where the data points are. It's certainly not the worst I've seen, the bar graph at least increases at consistent intervals. The gender of the creator honestly did not even cross my mind, and being asked to think about it threw me a bit. I put female pretty much just because of gender associations (I dislike this, but my immediate association with artsy leafy patterns like this is "female") and because I have noticed that more than half of the people on tumblr identify as female (every time a poll about user gender goes around it's always more female). I assume the creator was more left wing because I tend to associate environmentalism with left wing beliefs. Confrontational vs diplomatic was also difficult but again, cultural associations of "green leafy outdoorsy forest = peaceful" influenced my choice. I assume this person was more altruistic because to return to my previous answer I assume leftists tend more towards altruism but it usually wouldn't be the kind of thing I would assume based on a single graphic. Does share my values was almost impossible without knowing what the actual subject of the graph (again, this is where I likely would have passed on this image and not thought about it the second I realized there's no actual information here) but since I am in favor of environmentalism and assume that is what this graph is about I assume the creator shares some of my values. Trustworthy I left squarely in the middle because without any actual data and having no idea what this is truly representing I cannot judge whether it seems reliable or not. I tend to be wary of even people who share my views regarding the veracity of their data (though I am much more likely to doubt the veracity of data I see from graphs that I assume to be created by right wing creators).
0_Q_B0_TOOL_DETAIL: I have no idea if you can even make graphs in graphic design software, but it does not have the sleekness I would expect out of someone using advanced graphic software.  I am completely inexperienced with data visualization software that isn't related to maps, so I cannot comment on it. This image seems fairly advanced for general purpose software or the little I know of coding languages. I seems like it would likely be easier to figure out how to use a simple or base graphic design software than try and create something this complicated in, say, MS Word.
0_Q_B0_CHART_EXPLAIN: Once again, really difficult to say with the actual data. Whether the data seems reasonable regardless of if it is displayed less than perfectly, I would likely reblog or like it. Aesthetically pleasing - the leafy images are rather nice, but like I said the pink background is a bit jarring. Trusting this image again depends on what it's about, but the more I look the less professional it seems so I might be a bit skeptical. Cannot tell if it's meant to inform or persuade, but I'm leaning towards inform because of the different types of trees shown (rather than amounts). If I knew what this image was about there's a chance I would look up more information about the topic or source depending on how reasonable the data seemed and how much the topic interested me.
2_Q_B2_MAKER_DETAIL: Someone making a graph with some concept of data analysis.
2_Q_B2_MAKER_EXPLAIN: I put millennial for age because I do my default is to assume that the average poster is mid-20s to late 30s. I put male but barely if I have to assume a gender because of cultural associations with imagining that men are slightly more likely to create charts or organized graphs as lay people (I do know this is incorrect). Squarely in the middle for almost all the rest of these. This box chart is so very generic, it could apply to almost anything or be made by almost anyone. I would expect a little bit more slickness if it was, say, created by a news organization. But I've seen plenty of scientific papers that have this quality of graph - simple, but effective at getting the point across. Even then, it could be made by an individual who does know more about graphic design but wanted to quickly throw a chart together to demonstrate something unimportant like the distribution of their Beanie Babe collection and didn't care about making it look fancy.
2_Q_B2_TOOL_DETAIL: No idea what data visualization software is like, but I'm pretty sure I made graphs like this back in MS Word 2003.
2_Q_B2_CHART_EXPLAIN: Again, my options on this would be drastically shaped by what the subject matter is and what the source is. If I was made by an individual making specific data claims, I probably wouldn't trust it. However, if it was from a study or published paper that was backed up by sources I would be far more likely to trust. I doubt I would look up more info about it in either case - I'd assume it's not worth it to look up (if made by an unsourced individual I would assume it's wrong, visa versa for a paper). It's not aesthetically pleasing at all like the last one was, but it gets the job done and isn't visually offensive (no horridly clashing colors or anything).
2_Q_B2_CHART_TYPE: Either a box chart or a bar graph, I forget the exact titles. It's been awhile since beginning math.
3_Q_B2_MAKER_DETAIL: A nicer journal or academic paper maybe
3_Q_B2_MAKER_EXPLAIN: So here's where my personal expertise comes in - I love maps, have designed a multitude of maps, and am experienced in GIS. I'd assume a millennial made this because most of the GIS-savvy people I know are millennials. No idea on the gender. If they're a GIS person they likely have at least some experience with both graphic design and data analysis, though their personal expertise could go either way. Solidly in the middle for most of the answers because again, I have no idea what the subject is. I instinctually want to trust this data because it's displayed in a pleasing way but I have too much knowledge of how much data visualization on a map can be easily manipulated.
3_Q_B2_TOOL_DETAIL: Definitely not anything basic and likely not graphic design software either. It could be a programming language I guess, but it's so exact - it's likely made one of the mapmaking software products.
3_Q_B2_CHART_EXPLAIN: Literally because I love maps, and if I trusted the source I would likely reblog it (however I always check the source for maps - again, I know how easily map data can be manipulated).
4_Q_B2_MAKER_DETAIL: A major publication like the NYT
4_Q_B2_MAKER_EXPLAIN: Sorry if my answers get shorter, I running low on time. Gen X because the style looks older. No clue about the gender and only selected male because traditionally they're more likely to get hired (especially for stuff related to data). Professional graphic design because of the design detail and complexity. Possibly a professional in data analysis but also likely a graphic designer hired by a company who was given a data set to visualize. No idea about left vs right wing, would need to know what the data is. More confrontational, because it gives the sense of being part of a news article that is trying to "make a point" and gives the sense of something that was created with a definitive thesis statement in mind and not just a general "hey, fun fact, did you know". No strong opinion on self-serving vs altruistic without more data, though leaning ever so slightly towards self-serving because of the vaguely sensationalist vibes I'm getting. Probably mostly shares my values, but again, no idea. My instinct would be to assume this was trustworthy and I probably wouldn't look much into it. I don't have the ability to double check every single informational graphic that crosses my screen and would assume that something with this level of professionalism is correct. Actually, I finally looked closely at the numbers on the image rather than just the overall vibe and noticed that numbers in two of the different columns are displayed at DRASTICALLY different scales. I changed my "self-serving" and "trustworthy" scales accordingly. When such hugely different numbers are shown at such wonky scales, I become distrustful of the motives and conclusions being made. The data numbers might be correct, but I can see that there's an intent to manipulate how that data is perceived.
4_Q_B2_TOOL_DETAIL: I actually assumed it was hand drawn and then I remembered that everything is digital nowadays, so it was likely drawn into a computer program with a tablet or the like.
4_Q_B2_CHART_ACTION: post a comment,unfollow / block the source,NOTHING — just keep scrolling
4_Q_B2_CHART_EXPLAIN: I might post a comment about how disingenuous the design is, but I likely wouldn't bother, especially if other people have already mentioned it. It takes me a lot of effort to type out my thoughts and this doesn't deserve that much of my time and attention. I might unfollow or block the person the posting it, but that would depending on why they're posting it - they're posting it sincerely I would unfollow, if it was posted by someone for the sake of commenting on it I would likely read it then scroll by. (Also, only just noticed that the above questions were multiple choice. Sorry about missing that for my previous answers.)

1_Q_B1_MAKER_EXPLAIN: I have only ever seen data presented like this while in academia - it's a type of chart I would think only someone very familiar with data sciences and some degree of familiarity with visual presentation would use. As such I'd be more likely to trust it what first glance.
1_Q_B1_TOOL_DETAIL: Again, going with the way I'd make this personally, it would be data imported from excel into a specialised data visualisation program - perhaps even a open source one used in their field of study.
1_Q_B1_CHART_ACTION: share / repost,share / repost WITH comment,look up more information about the topic or source
1_Q_B1_CHART_EXPLAIN: The image immediately strikes me as engaging and informative and I'd certainly stop to read it and the rest of the post it's in. If it was about a topic I was interested in I'd probably reblog it without comment. However, if it was about a topic I had knowledge of, I'd very likely add my own comments and maybe even my own information/graphs.
2_Q_B1_MAKER_EXPLAIN: That this graph is so easy to read at a glance makes me feel as if this was made by someone trained in graphical design on behalf of someone who had already done the data analysis for them. The colour pallete strikes me as a more masculine choice. It looks as if it was designed to be placed in the middle of an article as a visual aid. I have no particular notion about the political leanings of the person who made the graph which makes me feel as if it was supposed to be presenting neutrality and therefore trustworthiness.
2_Q_B1_TOOL_DETAIL: I feel it was likely originally made in Excel then imported into whatever software was used to make the rest of the article as a graphic.
2_Q_B1_CHART_ACTION: look up more information about the topic or source,NOTHING — just keep scrolling
2_Q_B1_CHART_EXPLAIN: It's very clear and easy to read, which I feel is to its credit. For that same reason it presents itself as being trustworthy and I'd certainly quickly look it over while scrolling but any further action would depend entirely on what the source of the graph actually was.
3_Q_B1_MAKER_DETAIL: Right wing news source, probably one more based online than traditional print media
3_Q_B1_MAKER_EXPLAIN: Use of an American flag these days immediately makes me think more of right wing than left wing sources. I'm also more likely to see them as untrustworthy because of the run of fake news stuff that has been more prevalent in their these days. I also tend to find them more confrontational than not. The colour pallete seems more masculine to me. I think the use of the flag is probably serving a purpose to the point of the graph which which why I think it's more likely than not made by someone familiar with graphic design.
3_Q_B1_TOOL_DETAIL: Excel and specialised data visualisation software - the layout (specifically the tilt of the text) coupled with the high detail in the actual rate of changes in the graph makes me suspect that data was recorded in excel then imported and graphed in specialised software (or at least that is how I would make this graph)
3_Q_B1_CHART_EXPLAIN: It's a pretty graph but the flag pings it as more persuasive than informative to me - it also make me trust it a lot less. 4_Q_B1_MAKER_EXPLAIN: As it seems to be made by/for and academic setting I'm more instinctively likely to trust it but as I'm not from the US, I'm more unfamiliar with their educational practices so I think I'd go into reading it with neutrality and look to see what else was in the post. I don't think I'd have much in the way of preconceptions about who made this at first glance.
4_Q_B1_TOOL_DETAIL: Probably a vector program, but I'm not familiar with specifics of those types of software. It seems too graphically complex to be made in data visualisation software, specifically because of the pictogram that make up the bars and the trend arrows.
4_Q_B1_CHART_ACTION: look up more information about the topic or source
4_Q_B1_CHART_EXPLAIN: It looks to be made specifically to inform, in an educational setting, to me so I'd certainly be more likely to read it's context.
